OBSERVATIONS.

In this Ode Horace addresses some noble young lady under the name of Galatea, who is about to sturton a distant expedition. He tells her not to be afraid os omens, by which the wicked only are deterred from their purpose. He con- eludes with the story of Europa, though with what object it is difficult to determine. It seems uncertain whether by that example he wishes to deter Galatea from her voyage, or whether he thinks only to amuse her by the narrative.
